Introduction

Trends in sexual relationships and their determinants have been a nuanced and ongoing question among sociologists and sexual health professionals. Variation in the number of sexual partners between genders, ages, and within different regions has evolved over the years in response to economic, and social movements (Tillman, Brewster, and Holway 2019). In particular, the frequency at which young people are having sex has been on decline, particularily among young adults (Lei and South 2021). This is occuring despite a dults in the 2000s were more likely to have more sexual partners and be more willing to engage in casual sex that th those of the 80s and 90s (Twenge, Sherman, and Wells 2015). Exploring the role education plays in sexual health has also been a frequent point of discussion. Prior literature has re-evaluated the discussion about the discussion about academics and sex, indicating that when high school students choose to engage in sexual behavior has impacts on academic performance (Frisco 2008). However, additional liturature describes how time commitments may limit time available for long-term relationships and could lead individuals to have more short-term sexual interactions (Fielder and Carey 2010). This project investigate whether there is an association between ones high school academic performance and both their self-reported sexual partners over time and their self-reported frequency of sexual encounters. The data used in this study comes from the National Longitudinal Study of Youth from 1997 (NLSY97). The survey looks at 9884 people, born between 1980-1984. The data was collected through yearly interviews, from 1997 until 2008. The interviews collected information about employment, demographics, sexual activity, dating and marriage, family, health trends, and various other attributes. This study focuses on Information related to age when the respondent experiences puberty, age of first sex encounter, race, ethnicity, and sexual identity. These measures have been reported to be associated with sexual partners (Kan et al.2010). Our measure of academic performance is ones average GPA, and our dependent variables of interest are a respondents reported number of sexual encounters since the last interview and a respondents reported number of sexual partners since the last interview.

Kan, Marni L., Yen-hsin Alice Cheng, Nancy S. Landale, and Susan M. McHale. 2010. Longitudinal Predictors of Change in Number of Sexual Partners across Adolescence and Early Adulthood. Journal of Adolescent Health 46 (1): 2531. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jadohealth.2009.05.002.

Modeling

Sex Since DLI

This test shows that average HS GPA is not significant by itself. This gives a preliminary answer to our question Is Avg GPA a significant predictor of number of sexual encounters?

However, this basic model is a significant oversimplification of the picture, because people change over time. Our second model will account for the age and marriage / cohabitation status at the time of interview. The addition of these level one variables will hopefully allow us to isolate any impact the avg_GPA might have.

Level 1:

\[\log(\frac{\lambda_{ij}}{interview\_dist_{ij}}) = a_i + b_iAge_{ij}\] Level 2: \[a_i = \alpha_0 + \alpha_1Avg\_GPA_i + \alpha_2Marriage\_Status_{ij} + u_i\] \[b_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1Avg\_GPA +v_i\] Composite Model \[\log(\frac{\lambda_{ij}}{interview\_dist_{ij}}) = \alpha_0 + \alpha_1Avg\_GPA_i + \alpha_2Marriage\_Status_{ij} + u_i + (\beta_0 + \beta_1Avg\_GPA +v_i)Age_{ij}\]

Interpretation of Coefficients:

\(\alpha_0 = 4.38\): According to our model, a cohabitating 0-year old with a 0.0 high school GPA is expected to have had an average of 4.38 sexual encounters over the past year.

\(\alpha_1 = 0.138\): Holding marriage status constant, a 0-year-old individual is estimated to have had 0.138 more sexual encounters in the past year for each addition point in his or her high school GPA.

\(\alpha_2:\) Holding age and GPA constant, a {Divorced, Married, Never Married, Seperated, Widowed} individual is expected to have had {0.0497, 0.145, 0.789, 0.184, 0.449} fewer sexual encounters in the past year than an otherwise similar cohabitating individual

\(\beta_0 = -0.050:\) Holding marriage status constant, among individuals with a 0.0 high school GPA an increase of one year in age is associated with a decrease by 0.050 of number of sexual encounters in the past year.

\(\beta_1 = -0.00617:\) Holding marriage status constant, for each point of GPA in high school an individual has, an increase in age of one year is associated with a further decrease of 0.00617 sexual encounters in the past year.

\(\sigma_u = 1.879:\) For a given individual, the mean of the number of sexual encounters in each year for which they have responded, is expected to differ from the average of such means of all individuals by 1.879 sexual encounters.

\(\sigma_v = 0.0614:\) For each year of a respondents age, their number of sexual encounters in the past year is expected to differ from their average number of sexual encounters for all of their years, by 0.0614 sexual encounters.

\(\rho_{uv} = -0.81:\) The correlation between the random variables \(u_i\) and \(v_i\) is -0.81. This means that in general, a higher variance in number of sexual encounters early in ones life will tend to decrease as a persons age increases, and a low variance in number of sexual encounters early in ones life will tend to increase.

\(\alpha_1\) On average, after adjusting for the year, average GPA, Region, and whether they were co-habitating with a partner, men have 0.2 more sexual partners than women.

\(\alpha_2\) There is statistically significant evidence that on average, after adjusting for the year, Sex, Region, and whether they were co-habitating with a partner, unit increase in an individuals average GPA is associated with around 1 less reported sexual partner per interview distance.

\(\beta_0\): On average, after adjusting for the sex, average GPA, Region, and whether they were co-habitating with a partner, the average respondent is expected to report about 1 additional sexual partner each year

\(\delta_0\): On average, after adjusting for time, the sex, average GPA, Region the average respondent who is not co-habitating with a partner is expected to report about 1.37 more sexual partners than those who are co-habitating.

\(\sigma_u\) The respondent to respondent St.Deviation in number of sexual partners for those in the women in the north central who were not cohabitating with a partner is 1.4438

Data Limitations

The Data had a number of restrictions. Firstly, the data was self reported, so there are many possibilities for individuals to not accurately report. This has been noted to be common in prior studies of sexual self reporting surveys for a number of speculated reasons (Hallfors et al.2002). The self-reporting issues are particularly evident in the sexual frequency data, where the distribution indicates clear spikes in numbers in the 5 or 10s place. Considering this is likely not something that people keep track of explicitly, and the variation in the years between interviews on this questionnaire, It is probably that the variation in sexual frequency is actually under reported. Finally, a number of respondents were simply not asked either of the questions and had to be dropped from the study. Considering the private nature of reporting on sexual behavior, addressing this particular challenge is difficult to overcome.

Regarding model assumptions, for the model on sexual partners, the model we ran struggled with overdispersion. This seems likely as there was a significantly large number of 1s reported. This could be due to the reasons listed above. As a result, these limitations could be biasing the effects and overestimating the associations of different variables, including GPA. The mlm package doesnt have a negative binomial package, which would likely be a better fit for this data.

In particular, a number of respondents in the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth 97 did not have any responses recorded for sexual partners; this is likely due to other reporting issues with self reported data and likely could skew the results.

Methods

The National Longitudinal Study of Youth (1997) is a study which has followed American individuals born between 1980 and 1984, giving yearly interviews from 1997 to 2021. The questions were administered via a CAPI (Computer-Assisted Personal Interview) instrument, which helps guide the respondent through the process, and to ensure that invalid answers are not given. Sometimes, these tests are administered with an interview present in person, but this is not always the case. Some of the questions are self-administered.

Respondents were offered $10-20 per round of interviewing they participated in. Other incentives were sometimes offered.

Audience

The intended audience for this report is for a sociology journal that explores trends in sexual relationships. The goal would be an academic article about the data analysis involved in exploring social-sexual behavior. Our intention is to write to an audience who may have more knowledge about the literature and background in studying sexual relationships.
